              '<p>We&rsquo;re adding another five minutes to the guided meditation practice this week.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><a href="https://yogainternational.com/ecourse/6-week-meditation-challenge/5/2">20-Minute Guided Meditation</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This might be a good time to look back over your journal and notice any trends. Or, if you haven&rsquo;t been keeping a journal, it&rsquo;s not too late to start! I hope you are finding peace of mind and feeling relaxed and content, but it is true that sometimes sitting quietly with our minds brings us face to face with inner turmoil. Never fear! This is also progress, and the mind will gradually clear as we continue meditating and begin to resolve inner conflicts.</p>\n\n<p>All of us face stressful situations in life&mdash;challenges to our calmness and stability. Stress can inspire us to make changes and spur accomplishment, but if not managed properly, stress takes a heavy toll on our physical and mental health. Stress plays a role in many chronic diseases, as well as reduced quality of life, but meditation has been shown to mitigate the negative consequences. Read more about stress and how to manage it from Dr. Carrie Demers: <a href="https://yogainternational.com/ecourse/6-week-meditation-challenge/5/3">How to Rewire Your Stress Response</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Here are two stress-busting practices to restore physical and mental balance to your life. Restorative asana is wonderful for stress, fatigue, or simply when you&rsquo;re not feeling up to par. &nbsp;</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><a href="https://yogainternational.com/ecourse/6-week-meditation-challenge/5/4">Restorative Asana Session,</a> video with AnaMargret Sanchez</li>\n\t<li><a href="https://yogainternational.com/ecourse/6-week-meditation-challenge/5/5">Stress-Busting Practice and Relaxation</a>, video with Sandra Anderson&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This short sequence includes a guided relaxation. It can be used at the end of a longer sequence of your favorite postures, or on its own to release tension from the body and make it easy to relax deeply.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Here&rsquo;s another resource for &nbsp;managing stress&mdash;prayer. Prayer is one of the best ways to acknowledge problems in life, and to use the wellsprings of emotion to deepen and inspire your practice. Bring heart to your practice by saying a prayer in your own words or any prayer that touches your heart. Prayers can set the mood and intention at the beginning of your practice and provide a sense of closure at the end. Even a simple prayer like &ldquo;Om shantih, shantih, shantih&rdquo; may bring direction and joy to your practice.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Here are a couple of choices to get you started (Link), including the beloved St. Francis Prayer from the Christian tradition. You&rsquo;ll also find a number of prayers from the yoga tradition at <a href="https://www.himalayaninstitute.org/prayers/">HimalayanInstitute.org</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Enjoy meditation and your prayers this week!</p>',
            snippet:
              "We’re adding another five minutes to the guided meditation practice this week. 20-Minute Guided Meditation This might be a good time to look back over your journal and notice any trends. Or, if you haven’t been keeping a journal, it’s not too late to start! I hope you are finding peace of mind and feeling relaxed and content, but it is true that sometimes sitting quietly with our minds brings us face to face with inner turmoil. Never fear! This is also progress, and the mind will gradually clear as we continue meditating and begin to resolve inner conflicts. All of us face stressful situations...",
